The paper discusses the computational power and complexity of spiking neural networks, which are commonly used in the field of computational neuroscience and artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces canonical problems and defines hierarchies of complexity classes, which are topics typically studied in the sub-categories of cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper discusses the potential energy efficiency of neuromorphic architectures, which falls under the sub-categories of cs.SY (Systems and Control) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
